                        <p>Waxing up enables a "draft" constructing of a future prosthetic work that is made as a "mock up". With such waxed up work, in a real 3-D form,  a patient can see how his problem can be solved and he can also make suggestions about a final outlook of his teeth. <br>
                            <br>
                            For making a "wax up" it is necessary to take a dental impression before making any intervention in a patient's mouth. When a dentist has several possible solutions before him, he will selectively grind existing teeth, so that both sides involved in making a prosthetic replacement can enjoy the best possible solution. Also, with a "wax up" method we choose a method for final work. Of course, since this is a completely individualized approach, work requires a little more time.<br>
                            <br>
                            Process of making a "wax up" is relatively simple, but it requires a thorough work and expert knowledge so that the final result would be excellent. </p>
